{{Infobox person | name = Maria Dickin | image = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = Maria Elisabeth Dickin | birth_date = {{Birth date|1870|9|22}} | birth_place = [[United Kingdom]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1951|3|1|1870|9|22}} | death_place = United Kingdom | nationality = [[British people|British]] | other_names = Mia | occupation = Social reformer, animal welfare pioneer | years_active = | known_for = | notable_works = }}
'''Maria Elisabeth Dickin''' [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] (nickname, '''Mia'''; 22 September 1870 &ndash; 1 March 1951) was a social reformer<ref name="Long2013">{{cite book|last=Long|first=David|title=Animal Heroes: Inspiring true stories of courageous animals|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ewiFsD91lUMC&pg=PR12|date=14 March 2013|publisher=Random House|isbn=978-1-4481-6516-2|pages=12–}}</ref> and an animal welfare pioneer who founded the [[People's Dispensary for Sick Animals]] (PDSA) in 1917. Born in 1870 in [[London]], she was the oldest of eight children; her parents were William George Dickin, a [[Wesleyan]] minister, and Ellen Maria (née Exell). She married her first cousin, Arnold Francis Dickin, an accountant, in 1899; they had no children. She enjoyed music, literary work and philanthropy. Dickin died in London in 1951 of influenzal broncho-pneumonia.<ref name="odnb">Brian Harrison, ‘Dickin, Maria Elisabeth (1870–1951)’, Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Oxford University Press, 2004; online edn, May 2010 [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/53789, accessed 2 Aug 2011]</ref>
==Legacy== [[Image:Maria Dickin 1870 - 1951 Promoter of animal welfare and founder of the PDSA was born here.jpg|thumb|125px|right|Blue Plaque at Dickin's birthplace in [[London Borough of Hackney|Hackney]].]] The [[Dickin Medal]] is named after her.
A commemorative [[blue plaque]] was erected by [[English Heritage]] at Dickin's birthplace, 41 Cassland Road (formerly 1 Farringdon Terrace) in [[London Borough of Hackney|Hackney]] in October 2015.<ref name="Blue Plaque">{{cite web |url=http://www.english-heritage.org.uk/about-us/search-news/maria-dickin-blue-plaque |title=Blue plaque for animal welfare campaigner, Maria Dickin |work=News |publisher=English Heritage |date=2015-10-08 |accessdate=2015-10-28 }}</ref>
