{{for|the footballer|Vladimir Gaćinović (footballer)}} {{Infobox person | name = Vladimir Gaćinović | image = Vladimir Gaćinović (1890–1917).jpg | alt = | caption = | birth_name = Владимир Гаћиновић | birth_date = {{Birth date|1890|05|25|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Kačanj]], [[Condominium of Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[Austria-Hungary]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1917|08|11|1890|05|25}} | death_place = [[Fribourg]], Switzerland | nationality = | other_names = | occupation = | known_for = Creator of [[Young Bosnia]]; proponent of "[[tyrannicide]]" }} '''Vladimir Gaćinović''' ({{lang-sr-cyr|Владимир Гаћиновић}}; nicknamed ''Vlado''; 25 May 1890 – 11 August 1917) was a [[Serbs of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnian Serb]] essayist and revolutionary in [[Austria-Hungary]].<ref name="Fabijancic2010">{{cite book|last=Fabijancic|first=Tony|title=Bosnia: In the Footsteps of Gavrilo Princip|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=twSoAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA41|date=25 February 2010|publisher=University of Alberta|isbn=978-0-88864-753-5|page=41}}</ref> He was one of the leaders and organizers of the secret cells of the revolutionary movement, [[Young Bosnia]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Braničevo|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M7fsAAAAMAAJ|year=1968|publisher=Kulturno-prosvetna zajednica Požorevac|page=75<!-- |quote=Владимир Гаћиновић није био формалии воћа у ономе смислу у коме су код нас биле воће политичких партија; али он је и без тога био стварни воћа рсволуционарне Младе Босне, јер је он у њој био најважиија личност којој су ... -->}}</ref>
==Early life== Gaćinović was born in 1890 in the village of [[Kačanj]] within [[Bileća]] municipality, which was then administered by the Austro-Hungarian [[Condominium of Bosnia and Herzegovina]] (another source has his birthplace as Rudina village, also in Bileća).<ref name="Glenny2012">{{cite book|last=Glenny|first=Misha|title=The Balkans: Nationalism, War, and the Great Powers, 1804-2012: New and Updated|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LJqYbknmxjYC&pg=PT244|date=5 September 2012|publisher=House of Anansi|isbn=978-1-77089-274-3|page=244}}</ref> Gaćinović was the son of a [[Serbian Orthodox]] priest,<ref name="Hoare2007">{{cite book|last=Hoare|first=Marko Attila|title=The history of Bosnia: from the Middle Ages to the present day|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OWQtAQAAIAAJ|year=2007|publisher=Saqi|isbn=978-0-86356-953-1|page=88}}</ref> who was also a [[hajduk]]. He completed elementary school in [[Bileća]] in 1901 and finished six grades of high school in [[Mostar]] between 1901 and 1907. The high school had been home to two secret societies since 1905, one of which, "Matica", was led by [[Dimitrije Mitrinović]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Istorijski glasnik|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pnE6AQAAIAAJ|year=1967|publisher=Naučna knjiga|page=96|quote=Рођен 1890. у билећком селу Качњу, као син свештеника који је био и хајдук, основну школу Гаћиновић је свршио... }}</ref> When he was seventeen years old, Gaćinović was a member of the literary society which served as a front for "Matica", and published a critically noted essay about the raconteur [[Petar Kočić]].<ref name="Митриновић1991">{{cite book|last=Митриновић|first=Димитрије|title=Sabrana djela: O književnosti i umjetnosti|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iY5iAAAAMAAJ|year=1991|publisher=Свјетлост|page=23<!-- |quote=...терарног клуба »Матица« сачињавали су Драго Перовић, Ва- сиљ Поповић и Перо Слијепчевић, затим Јован Старовић, Бог- дан Жерајић и Владимир Гаћиновић, који је у »Матици«, као седамнаестогодишњи младић, поднео .. -->}}</ref>
==Young Bosnia and Kosovo tyrannicide== {{Quote box | quote ="Gaćinović's friends and followers were mostly like him — quiet, young, undernourished, intense, swinging furiously between moods of sentimentality and ruthless revolutionary aggression."<ref name=Glenny2012 /> | source = [[Misha Glenny]] | width =25% | align =left }} Austria-Hungary's [[Bosnian crisis|complete annexation of Bosnia and Herzegovina]] in 1908 angered young revolutionaries active in that region. They rejected the conciliatory ideas of [[Tomáš Garrigue Masaryk]] and his [[Austro-Slavism|cultural struggle within the Austrian monarchy]]; instead, they embraced the notion of "Kosovo [[tyrannicide]]", à la [[Miloš Obilić]], as a method of political struggle.<ref name="Мастиловић2009">{{cite book|last=Мастиловић|first=Драга|title=Херцеговина у Краљевини Срба, Хрвата и Словенаца: 1918-1929|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_motAQAAIAAJ|year=2009|publisher=Филип Вишњић|isbn=978-86-7363-604-7|page=35<!-- |quote=Анексија Босне и Херцеговине јако је погодила те младе рево- луционаре, па неки од њих врло рано напуштају Масарикове идеје „културне борбе" и прихватају култ „косовског тираноубиства" као метод политичке борбе. -->}}</ref> Gaćinović was the actual ideologue<ref name="armije1968">{{cite book|author=Belgrade (Serbia). Vojni muzej Jugoslovenske narodne armije|title=Fourteen centuries of struggle for freedom|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2m8MAQAAMAAJ|year=1968|publisher=The Military Museum|page=li<!-- |quote=Vladimir Gacinovic was the ideologist of "Young Bosnia", while Gavrilo Princip was its central personality. --> }}</ref> of the revolutionary movement [[Young Bosnia]], and was thus responsible for introducing the cult of tyrannicide.<ref name="ЛесковацФоришковић2004">{{cite book|last1=Лесковац|first1=Младен|last2=Форишковић|first2=Александар|last3=Попов|first3=Чедомир|title=Српски биографски речник|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ozYYAQAAIAAJ|year=2004|publisher=Будућност|page=634<!-- |quote=Стварни организатор тајних кружока „Младе Босне" и идеолог тираноубиства, -->}}</ref> [[Bogdan Žerajić]] was the first to pursue this method in practice. When [[Franz Joseph I of Austria]] visited Bosnia and Herzegovina on 3 June 1910, Žerajić had intended to attempt his assassination during his passage through Mostar, but eventually gave up his plan for unknown reasons.<ref name="Мастиловић2009 2">{{cite book|last=Мастиловић|first=Драга|title=Херцеговина у Краљевини Срба, Хрвата и Словенаца: 1918-1929|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_motAQAAIAAJ|year=2009|publisher=Филип Вишњић|isbn=978-86-7363-604-7|page=35<!-- |quote=Приликом посјете цара Фрање Јосифа Босни и Херцеговини, почетком јуна 1910. године, Жерајић се ... -->}}</ref> Žerajić attempted to assassinate Austro-Hungarian governor [[Marijan Varešanin]] in Sarajevo a week later, but killed himself when the plot failed.<ref>{{cite book|title=Srpski književni glasnik|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wwFEAAAAIAAJ|year=1935|page=451<!-- |quote=У јесен 1910, у знак протеста против новоствореног Сабора, који није имао ниједну ознаку највише законодавне и политичке установе у земљи, пуцаће херцеговачки студент Богдан Жерајић на генерала В а р е ш а н и н а, ... -->}}</ref>
Gaćinović, who was personal friends with European socialists such as [[Victor Serge]] and [[Julius Martov]],<ref name=Horvat2014>{{cite news|last1=Horvat|first1=Srećko|title=First world war: was Gavrilo Princip a terrorist or a freedom fighter?|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/apr/15/first-world-war-gavrilo-princip-terrorist-freedom-fighter-revisionism|accessdate=10 July 2014|publisher=The Guardian|date=15 April 2014}}</ref> met [[Leon Trotsky]] by chance in Paris. His revolutionary zeal impressed Trotsky.<ref name="Avdić2014">{{cite news|last1=Avdić|first1=Selvedin|title=Selvedin Avdić: A Great War Library|url=http://www.guernicamag.com/daily/selvedin-avdic-a-great-war-library/|accessdate=10 July 2014|publisher=Guernica|date=30 June 2014}}</ref> From autumn 1910 to the summer of 1912, Gaćinović was a student at [[Vienna University]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Dedijer|first=Vladimir|authorlink=Vladimir Dedijer|title=Sarajevo hiljadu devetstso četraneste|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QTdIAAAAMAAJ|year=1966|publisher=Prosveta|page=834<!-- |quote=Од јесени 1910. до лета 1912. Гаћиновић је, као студент филозофије, похађао Бечки универзитет у току четири семе- стра. -->}}</ref> In his late teens, after visiting the [[Kingdom of Serbia]], Gaćinović organized underground cells, ''kruzoks'', amongst Serbs in Bosnia and Herzegovina, [[Zagreb]], and western [[Slavonia]]. In 1911, he became the only Young Bosnia leader to join [[Black Hand (Serbia)|Unification or Death]], [[Dragutin Dimitrijević]]'s secret society.<ref name=Glenny2012 /> In the same year, the term ''Mlada Bosna'' (Young Bosnia) was popularized in an article by Gaćinović, and modeled by him after [[Young Italy]] and [[Nabat|Young Russia]].<ref name=Glenny2012 /> In 1912, Gaćinović publicized a letter by one of his associates, with whom he fully agreed. Titled "Cry of a Desperate One" ({{lang-sr|Крик очајника}}), it attacked the younger generations, in particular students at foreign universities, for lack of idealism and opportunism, petty individualism, and conformity.<ref>{{cite book|title=Историјски гласник: орган Друштва историчара СР Србије|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7nZMAQAAIAAJ|year=1967|publisher=Društvo|page=109}}</ref>
During the [[First Balkan War]], Gaćinović fought as a volunteer in the [[Montenegrin Ground Army|Montenegrin army]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Историјски гласник: орган Друштва историчара СР Србије|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7nZMAQAAIAAJ|year=1967|publisher=Društvo|page=100<!-- |quote=Као добровољац у цриогорској војсци, Гаћиновић је учествовао у оисади Скадра. Пошто се та опсада одуљила, а рат је на осталим фронтовима био за- вршен, добровољци су могли отићи. Гаћиновић је по- ловином јануара 1913 ... -->}}</ref> Upon his return to Bosnia, he instigated a plot to kill [[Oskar Potiorek]], the Austrian Governor, in January 1914, but did not follow through with his own plan.<ref name=Preston2014>{{cite news|last1=Preston|first1=Richard|title=First World War centenary: the assassination of Franz Ferdinand, as it happened|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/history/world-war-one/10930863/First-World-War-centenary-the-assassination-of-Franz-Ferdinand-as-it-happened.html|accessdate=10 July 2014|work=The Telegraph|date=27 June 2014}}</ref> Nevertheless, Gaćinović publicly condemned in his letters the subsequent [[Assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria|assassination of Franz Ferdinand]]. According to some sources, this was merely an attempt to avoid prosecution for his involvement; however, other authors have it that Gaćinović was sincerely opposed to the assassination.<ref>{{cite book|last=Dedijer|first=Vladimir|authorlink=Vladimir Dedijer|title=Sarajevo hiljadu devetstso četraneste|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QTdIAAAAMAAJ|year=1966|publisher=Prosveta|page=522<!-- |quote=Могло би се претпоставити да је Гаћиновић ова писма пи- сао одмах после 28. јуна 1914, да би скинуо са себе одговорност за атентат и његове последице. Мећутим, један други извор потврћује да је Гаћиновић заиста тако... -->}}</ref>
During [[World War I]], Gaćinović spent time as a volunteer in the [[French Navy]], after which he traveled to the [[United States]] to seek aid and volunteers for Serbia. He was poisoned with [[arsenic]] in August 1917 in Fribourg, Switzerland, by either the Austrians, the French, the Serbian police, or by one of Serbia's rival political factions.<ref>{{cite book | last = Dedijer | first = Vladimir | authorlink = Vladimir Dedijer | year = 1966 | title = The Road to Sarajevo | publisher = Simon and Schuster | location = New York | oclc = 400010 | pages = 184–283 }}</ref>
